                <h1>Duke undergrad Young Trustee finalist selection raises questions on conflict of interest</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/9e300a5b-9f70-41ac-b0cf-03e5904df3e3.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="This&#x20;chart&#x20;depicts&#x20;the&#x20;network&#x20;of&#x20;both&#x20;close&#x20;and&#x20;business-like&#x20;relationships&#x20;between&#x20;Young&#x20;Trustee&#x20;Nominating&#x20;Committee&#x20;members&#x20;and&#x20;the&#x20;YT&#x20;semifinalists,&#x20;as&#x20;disclosed&#x20;by&#x20;the&#x20;committee.&#x20;A&#x20;previous&#x20;version&#x20;of&#x20;this&#x20;graphic&#x20;did&#x20;not&#x20;indicate&#x20;Brandon&#x20;Putnam&#x20;and&#x20;Jay&#x20;Kennedy&#x20;as&#x20;DSG&#x20;affiliates." class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            This chart depicts the network of both close and business-like relationships between Young Trustee Nominating Committee members and the YT semifinalists, as disclosed by the committee. A previous version of this graphic did not indicate Brandon Putnam and Jay Kennedy as DSG affiliates.

                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/carleigh-stiehm">Carleigh Stiehm</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">January 30, 2013 | 7:14am EST</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2013/01/duke-undergrad-young-trustee-finalist-selection-raises-questions-conflict-interest" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2013/01/duke-undergrad-young-trustee-finalist-selection-raises-questions-conflict-interest&amp;text=Duke undergrad Young Trustee finalist selection raises questions on conflict of interest" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Duke%20undergrad%20Young%20Trustee%20finalist%20selection%20raises%20questions%20on%20conflict%20of%20interest%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2013%2F01%2Fduke-undergrad-young-trustee-finalist-selection-raises-questions-conflict-interest" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>The members of the Young Trustee Nominating Committee declared eight major and 13 minor conflicts of interest in relation to the Young Trustee semifinalists.</p>
<p>Major conflicts of interest led members of the committee—which narrowed the eight Young Trustee applicants down to three finalists Jan. 21—to remove themselves from voting on the candidate in question, but not from voting on the others. The connections between the YTNC members and the Young Trustee semifinalists posed a challenge to the ability of the committee to select finalists in an unbiased manner.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>Since the committee selected the three finalists who are currently campaigning for election by the student body, several members have begun publicly supporting one or more of the candidates that the committee selected.</p>
<p>The YTNC sought to avoid bias during its selection process by allowing members with conflicts of interest to excuse themselves from the deliberations on candidates, said YTNC Chair Daniel Pellegrino, a junior.</p>
<p>“As far as conflicts of interest are concerned, any YTNC member that knows an applicant must make this known to the committee, and we told all of the applicants about the potential conflicts of interest prior to the interviews,” Pellegrino wrote in an email Tuesday. “If a member has a major conflict of interest—such as a close friendship with an applicant—they are able to remove themselves from deliberations on that applicant, meaning they cannot comment on that person or vote on them.”</p>
<p>If an applicant felt that a member should have declared a major conflict with any applicant, they were given the opportunity to protest, Pellegrino said.
Pellegrino defined a major conflict of interest as “significant personal relationship that irrevocably impairs the YTNC member’s ability to pass impartial judgment.”</p>
<p>He defined a minor conflict of interest as “a business relationship where the YTNC member’s ability to pass impartial judgment is not affected by the relationship and where the relationship may in fact help the member better assess the qualifications of the candidate.”</p>
<p>Although members of the YTNC have the ability to excuse themselves from deliberations on a candidate that they have a relationship with, they do not need to recuse themselves from voting on the other candidates.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>“A few YTNC members know they will endorse a person should they become a finalist (because of a previous friendship), but this wouldn’t help that person in becoming a finalist because the committee member would remove themselves from deliberations and voting on that person (and essentially vote on the remaining applicants as if the conflict applicant didn’t exist),” Pellegrino wrote.</p>
<p>The procedure, however, might not be able to remove the effect of personal relationships from Young Trustee selection, said Young Trustee finalist Gurdane Bhutani, a senior.</p>
<p>“It is only natural that some people on the committee are going to be friends with some of the applicants, and this may have an effect on their judgment,” Bhutani said.</p>
<p><strong>DSG presence</strong></p>
                            
    
<div class="mc-signup my-4 p-4 text-center " id="mc-container" data-mc="c4087a59c7">
    <h3>Get The Chronicle straight to your inbox</h3>
    <p>Signup for our editorially curated, weekly newsletter. Cancel at any time.</p>
    <div class="row">
        <div class="col col-md-8 offset-md-2">
            <form action="//dukechronicle.us4.list-manage.com/subscribe/post?u=c49dc69f492af7f2727860d0b&amp;id=c4087a59c7" method="post">
                <div class="input-group">
                    <input type="email" name="EMAIL" class="form-control form-control-sm" placeholder="Your email address" />
                    <input type="hidden" value="1" name="group[29][1]" id="mce-group[29]-29-0">

                    <div class="input-group-append">
                        <input type="submit" value="Subscribe" class="btn btn-secondary btn-sm sends-events" data-ga-category="CTA" data-ga-action="email_focus" data-ga-label="c4087a59c7" />
